1
00:00:01,600 --> 00:00:05,400
[♪]

2
00:01:01,700 --> 00:01:03,333
TRAFFIC ROBOT:
And a one, and a two.

3
00:01:03,366 --> 00:01:05,166
Okay, step lively there, folks.

4
00:01:05,200 --> 00:01:07,666
The signal says "walk,"
not "crawl."

5
00:01:07,700 --> 00:01:09,766
You think I got all day
to stand here?

6
00:01:09,800 --> 00:01:12,566
Well, maybe I do, but I need you
to keep moving along.
Move along. Move along.

7
00:01:12,600 --> 00:01:14,266
<i>The special robot nominees</i>
<i>were announced this morning</i>

8
00:01:14,300 --> 00:01:16,100
<i>for the first annual</i>
<i>Robot of the Year award,</i>

9
00:01:16,133 --> 00:01:19,233
<i>which will honor the robot</i>
<i>who has best exemplified</i>

10
00:01:19,266 --> 00:01:22,200
<i>the human-like qualities</i>
<i>of courage, heart and mind.</i>

11
00:01:22,233 --> 00:01:23,666
<i>The gala event</i>
<i>will be held here,</i>

12
00:01:23,700 --> 00:01:24,900
<i>aboard the world's</i>

13
00:01:24,933 --> 00:01:27,366
<i>largest luxury liner,</i>
<i>the</i> Carmela Queen.

14
00:01:27,400 --> 00:01:29,366
<i>Here to give us his thoughts</i>
<i>on this special occasion</i>

15
00:01:29,400 --> 00:01:31,766
<i>is world-famous scientist</i>
<i>Dr. O'Shay.</i>

16
00:01:31,800 --> 00:01:33,733
<i>Since the Blue Knight</i>
<i>incident...</i>

17
00:01:33,766 --> 00:01:35,166
Boys, I think
you'll wanna see this.

18
00:01:35,200 --> 00:01:36,333
Cool! Yeah!

19
00:01:36,366 --> 00:01:38,266
ALEJO:
Just think,
I knew him when!

20
00:01:38,300 --> 00:01:40,600
<i>But the truth is most robots</i>

21
00:01:40,633 --> 00:01:42,766
<i>just simply want</i>
<i>to be our friends.</i>

22
00:01:42,800 --> 00:01:44,300
REPORTER:
Astro!
Huh? Hey!

23
00:01:44,333 --> 00:01:46,300
Congratulations,
Astro.

24
00:01:46,333 --> 00:01:47,400
[BOYS LAUGHING]

25
00:01:47,433 --> 00:01:49,033
Cool!

26
00:01:49,066 --> 00:01:50,666
Astro, tell the folks at home

27
00:01:50,700 --> 00:01:53,166
how you feel about being
nominated for the big award.

28
00:01:53,200 --> 00:01:55,066
Huh? I was?

29
00:01:55,100 --> 00:01:57,633
ALEJO:
Yeah! Astro is
number one!

30
00:01:57,666 --> 00:01:59,766
Well, Astro,
<i>what do you say?</i>

31
00:01:59,800 --> 00:02:03,600
<i>Uh, it's an honor</i>
<i>just to be nominated.</i>

32
00:02:03,633 --> 00:02:05,633
Ridiculous.

33
00:02:05,666 --> 00:02:08,600
The fools are actually planning
to give a robot an award?

34
00:02:08,633 --> 00:02:10,033
Robots are tools!

35
00:02:10,066 --> 00:02:11,033
No matter.

36
00:02:11,066 --> 00:02:12,600
Once they're onboard the ship,

37
00:02:12,633 --> 00:02:16,033
I'll blast these "robots of
the year" into the next century!

38
00:02:16,066 --> 00:02:18,400
Why do you hate
robots so much?

39
00:02:18,433 --> 00:02:19,500
[GASPS]

40
00:02:20,766 --> 00:02:22,600
I always tried to help you.

41
00:02:24,533 --> 00:02:26,500
Don't you
remember?

42
00:02:26,533 --> 00:02:29,800
I was your...
friend.

43
00:02:29,833 --> 00:02:34,066
I told you before,
I don't know who you are!

44
00:02:34,100 --> 00:02:36,200
Now, for the last time,
leave me alone!

45
00:02:39,800 --> 00:02:41,666
[MOANS]

46
00:02:41,700 --> 00:02:45,066
Why? Why won't he let me be?

47
00:02:47,066 --> 00:02:48,400
How did I get into this mess?

48
00:02:48,433 --> 00:02:52,300
I must be crazy,
flying in these conditions,

49
00:02:52,333 --> 00:02:54,166
but I must get
to the robot factory.

50
00:02:54,200 --> 00:02:55,166
[GROANS]

51
00:02:58,400 --> 00:03:00,633
Yes, this is the chance
I've been waiting for,

52
00:03:00,666 --> 00:03:02,433
to step out of
my father's shadow

53
00:03:02,466 --> 00:03:04,300
and show everyone I can run
the family business

54
00:03:04,333 --> 00:03:06,400
better than
he ever did.

55
00:03:06,433 --> 00:03:08,700
Well, it's going to take
more than a little rain

56
00:03:08,733 --> 00:03:10,400
to keep me away
from that factory.

57
00:03:15,133 --> 00:03:16,133
[SCREAMING]

58
00:03:30,207 --> 00:03:31,141
[SCREAMING]

59
00:03:37,441 --> 00:03:39,407
TV HOST:
<i>Our next nominee is Epsilon,</i>

60
00:03:39,441 --> 00:03:40,607
a strong favorite for her work

61
00:03:40,641 --> 00:03:42,641
<i>in the fields of science</i>
<i>and the environment.</i>

62
00:03:42,674 --> 00:03:46,374
<i>She's coming to us from</i>
<i>the uninhabited Caldera Island</i>

63
00:03:46,407 --> 00:03:48,441
<i>where she is working with</i>
<i>a geological survey team.</i>

64
00:03:48,474 --> 00:03:50,407
Caldera Island?

65
00:03:50,441 --> 00:03:53,474
<i>Ten years ago...</i>
<i>Caldera Island was the site</i>

66
00:03:53,507 --> 00:03:56,141
<i>of one of the largest</i>
<i>volcanic eruptions on record.</i>

67
00:03:56,174 --> 00:03:58,141
Coincidence?

68
00:03:58,174 --> 00:04:00,141
No, it's more.

69
00:04:00,174 --> 00:04:02,241
Timing like this,
it has to be destiny!

70
00:04:02,274 --> 00:04:05,274
Epsilon's been busy surveying
the very large crater.

71
00:04:05,307 --> 00:04:07,774
Come in, Epsilon. Come in!

72
00:04:07,807 --> 00:04:09,674
Can you tell us
what you've discovered?

73
00:04:09,707 --> 00:04:13,441
Yes. Pressure is building again
inside the magma chamber.

74
00:04:13,474 --> 00:04:18,107
However, she's not likely to
erupt for...another six months.

75
00:04:18,141 --> 00:04:19,207
DAN:
<i>Return to base.</i>

76
00:04:19,241 --> 00:04:21,207
On my way.

77
00:04:21,241 --> 00:04:23,674
Good work.
You did a fine job.

78
00:04:23,707 --> 00:04:25,241
Epsilon,
over here.

79
00:04:25,274 --> 00:04:28,241
Could you tell us
what you'll be
wearing tonight?

80
00:04:28,274 --> 00:04:29,074
MAN: Hey!
Huh?

81
00:04:29,107 --> 00:04:32,241
Captain, I think
you'll wanna see this.

82
00:04:32,274 --> 00:04:33,774
There's something
buried here.

83
00:04:35,741 --> 00:04:38,174
Huh.
It's a robot.

84
00:04:38,207 --> 00:04:41,107
A type I've never
seen before.

85
00:04:41,141 --> 00:04:42,774
ANNOUNCER:
<i>Robots, ladies and gentlemen,</i>

86
00:04:42,807 --> 00:04:46,074
<i>welcome aboard</i>
<i>the</i> Carmela Queen.

87
00:04:46,107 --> 00:04:49,241
Wow,
it's humongous!

88
00:04:49,274 --> 00:04:52,807
Maybe next year
I'll be nominated
for an award.

89
00:04:52,841 --> 00:04:54,074
Hey,
Harley!

90
00:04:54,107 --> 00:04:56,507
Astro! It's been a while.

91
00:04:56,541 --> 00:04:58,441
Wow!
It's Harley!

92
00:04:58,474 --> 00:05:00,474
[LAUGHS]

93
00:05:00,507 --> 00:05:02,441
I have all
of your holoposters.

94
00:05:02,474 --> 00:05:04,307
If you want, you can
autograph them for me.

95
00:05:04,341 --> 00:05:06,274
And then Astro can take
our picture together,

96
00:05:06,307 --> 00:05:08,607
and then you could teach me
<i>some cool moves.</i>

97
00:05:12,407 --> 00:05:14,307
Gordon here, boss.

98
00:05:14,341 --> 00:05:18,407
Navi-computer will be online
in two minutes.

99
00:05:18,441 --> 00:05:21,474
<i>Then you'll be in complete</i>
<i>control of the ship.</i>

100
00:05:21,507 --> 00:05:22,507
DRAKE:
Good. Get out!

101
00:05:22,541 --> 00:05:23,541
<i>Roger!</i>

102
00:05:23,574 --> 00:05:25,341
Kato, this is Drake.

103
00:05:25,374 --> 00:05:26,674
What's the delay?

104
00:05:26,707 --> 00:05:29,074
<i>Perfection takes time.</i>

105
00:05:29,107 --> 00:05:31,641
<i>And it doesn't get</i>
<i>more perfect than this.</i>

106
00:05:31,674 --> 00:05:35,541
DRAKE:
<i>Words mean nothing.</i>
<i>I want fireworks!</i>

107
00:05:35,574 --> 00:05:37,407
<i>Relax, boss-man.</i>

108
00:05:37,441 --> 00:05:39,774
<i>"Fireworks" doesn't</i>
<i>begin to describe it.</i>

109
00:05:39,807 --> 00:05:41,374
<i>[LAUGHS]</i>

110
00:05:43,741 --> 00:05:47,607
The ship will be caught
in the eruption, then sink.

111
00:05:47,641 --> 00:05:51,174
And then we'll hear no more
of thinking, feeling robots

112
00:05:51,207 --> 00:05:52,241
or those
who support them.

113
00:05:52,274 --> 00:05:53,274
[LAUGHS]

114
00:05:53,307 --> 00:05:54,574
BUDDY'S VOICE:
Why?
Huh?

115
00:05:56,574 --> 00:06:00,341
Why did you...abandon me there?

116
00:06:00,374 --> 00:06:01,707
[PANTS DELIRIOUSLY]

117
00:06:01,741 --> 00:06:03,707
Buddy!

118
00:06:05,474 --> 00:06:07,541
[PANTS]

119
00:06:13,207 --> 00:06:16,041
A thousand miles
from civilization.

120
00:06:17,341 --> 00:06:19,574
Transmitter broken.

121
00:06:19,607 --> 00:06:22,241
Only two days of food and water.

122
00:06:22,274 --> 00:06:23,041
Huh?

123
00:06:25,507 --> 00:06:26,607
It's hopeless.

124
00:06:26,641 --> 00:06:28,807
I won't last the week
on this island.

125
00:06:28,841 --> 00:06:30,374
Mr. Drake?
Huh?

126
00:06:30,407 --> 00:06:33,274
What? You!

127
00:06:33,307 --> 00:06:34,207
You're the new
artificial intelligence robot

128
00:06:34,241 --> 00:06:37,541
scheduled for display
at the trade fair!

129
00:06:37,574 --> 00:06:39,241
Cheer up, please.

130
00:06:39,274 --> 00:06:43,474
I'm sure
you'll be rescued
before long.

131
00:06:45,741 --> 00:06:47,407
ZORAN:
How long, huh?
Huh?

132
00:06:47,441 --> 00:06:49,107
How long until
they announce the winner?

133
00:06:49,141 --> 00:06:50,074
O'SHAY:
Patience, Zoran.
Patience.

134
00:06:50,107 --> 00:06:51,107
ROBOT WAITRESS:
Hors d'oeuvres?

135
00:06:51,141 --> 00:06:53,474
Canapés?
Motor oil?

136
00:06:53,507 --> 00:06:54,507
[ALL LAUGH]

137
00:06:57,707 --> 00:07:02,207
Epsilon,
are you excited?
Of course.

138
00:07:02,241 --> 00:07:04,741
Whoa, what a sunset!

139
00:07:04,774 --> 00:07:06,174
Hmm.
Huh? What's wrong?

140
00:07:06,207 --> 00:07:08,374
Aren't you
having fun?

141
00:07:08,407 --> 00:07:10,574
All day I've had
the feeling

142
00:07:10,607 --> 00:07:12,207
something bad
was going to happen.

143
00:07:12,241 --> 00:07:13,041
Huh.

144
00:07:15,241 --> 00:07:17,207
DRAKE:
No, this couldn't
have gone better

145
00:07:17,241 --> 00:07:19,241
if I'd
planned it myself.

146
00:07:19,274 --> 00:07:21,774
Ha-ha, that's right! I did.

147
00:07:21,807 --> 00:07:24,441
Right on schedule too.

148
00:07:24,474 --> 00:07:27,207
Now, as the new captain
of the <i>Carmela Queen,</i>

149
00:07:27,241 --> 00:07:29,307
I think I'll plot
a slight change in course.

150
00:07:29,341 --> 00:07:33,307
Say, 20 degrees starboard.

151
00:07:33,341 --> 00:07:35,141
<i>Yes, that should do nicely.</i>

152
00:07:35,174 --> 00:07:37,841
Look at the unwitting fools!

153
00:07:37,874 --> 00:07:40,441
Enjoy the party, my friends!

154
00:07:40,474 --> 00:07:43,641
But I'm the one
with a reason to celebrate.

155
00:07:43,674 --> 00:07:46,774
After 10 years, my long
nightmare is about to end,

156
00:07:46,807 --> 00:07:48,107
but yours
is just beginning!

157
00:07:57,141 --> 00:08:00,674
MC:
Now, before we announce
tonight's winner, Dr. O'Shay?

158
00:08:00,707 --> 00:08:01,707
O'SHAY:
Thank you.

159
00:08:01,741 --> 00:08:03,207
Each of our nominees

160
00:08:03,241 --> 00:08:04,207
has displayed
the miraculous qualities

161
00:08:04,241 --> 00:08:07,141
of heart,
mind and courage.

162
00:08:07,174 --> 00:08:10,207
This made the job of picking
a winner rather difficult.

163
00:08:10,241 --> 00:08:12,274
I'd like to dedicate today
to putting the past behind us

164
00:08:12,307 --> 00:08:13,407
and finding a new

165
00:08:13,441 --> 00:08:16,541
<i>understanding between humans</i>
<i>and robots.</i>

166
00:08:16,574 --> 00:08:19,407
A new understanding between
humans and robots?

167
00:08:19,441 --> 00:08:20,807
Never!

168
00:08:23,707 --> 00:08:24,941
<i>Day after day,</i>

169
00:08:24,974 --> 00:08:28,374
<i>the robot brought me</i>
<i>whatever food he could gather.</i>

170
00:08:28,407 --> 00:08:30,807
<i>I hadn't asked for help</i>
<i>and I didn't want any.</i>

171
00:08:30,841 --> 00:08:34,074
<i>But there he was every day</i>
<i>just the same,</i>

172
00:08:34,107 --> 00:08:38,807
<i>doing what he could</i>
<i>to ease my solitary existence.</i>

173
00:08:38,841 --> 00:08:41,174
<i>At first, I didn't know</i>
<i>what to make of it.</i>

174
00:08:41,207 --> 00:08:43,541
<i>Why was he doing all of this?</i>

175
00:08:43,574 --> 00:08:45,207
<i>The last thing I wanted</i>
<i>was pity</i>

176
00:08:45,241 --> 00:08:48,441
<i>from some walking</i>
<i>pile of scrap metal.</i>

177
00:08:48,474 --> 00:08:50,041
Huh?

178
00:08:54,574 --> 00:08:56,341
Look,
Mr. Drake.

179
00:08:56,374 --> 00:08:58,374
I found some papayas
this morning.

180
00:08:58,407 --> 00:09:00,074
They're very
nutritious,

181
00:09:00,107 --> 00:09:01,341
and I understand
that humans

182
00:09:01,374 --> 00:09:02,807
find them
quite tasty.

183
00:09:02,841 --> 00:09:05,241
What would you know
about it?

184
00:09:05,274 --> 00:09:06,641
Stupid robot!

185
00:09:09,341 --> 00:09:11,241
Are they good?

186
00:09:11,274 --> 00:09:13,507
Oh, they're terrible.

187
00:09:13,541 --> 00:09:15,441
You're completely
useless.

188
00:09:15,474 --> 00:09:17,407
Go away!

189
00:09:17,441 --> 00:09:20,407
I'm sorry. I'll just
dispose of the remainder.

190
00:09:20,441 --> 00:09:23,107
Perhaps the sand crabs
will find them to their liking.

191
00:09:23,141 --> 00:09:24,774
Don't trouble
yourself!

192
00:09:24,807 --> 00:09:26,607
I'll just force myself
to eat the rest.

193
00:09:28,107 --> 00:09:29,674
I'm just joking with you.

194
00:09:29,707 --> 00:09:31,507
You're joking?

195
00:09:31,541 --> 00:09:33,374
[LAUGHS]

196
00:09:34,507 --> 00:09:37,507
[LAUGHS]

197
00:09:37,541 --> 00:09:39,274
<i>He gave me</i>
<i>the strength to go on.</i>

198
00:09:39,307 --> 00:09:41,474
<i>Me? I gave him a name.</i>

199
00:09:41,507 --> 00:09:42,441
<i>I called him Buddy.</i>

200
00:09:45,241 --> 00:09:48,541
I was completely wrong
about robots.

201
00:09:48,574 --> 00:09:51,207
Buddy, you're not just
a walking computer.

202
00:09:51,241 --> 00:09:53,774
You have a heart
as well as a mind.

203
00:09:53,807 --> 00:09:56,174
So do you, Mr. Drake.

204
00:09:56,207 --> 00:09:57,607
MC:
Finally, ladies
and gentlemen...

205
00:09:57,641 --> 00:09:59,374
here to name
the first annual

206
00:09:59,407 --> 00:10:02,741
Robot of the Year award winner,
Dr. O'Shay.

207
00:10:02,774 --> 00:10:04,507
Thank you.

208
00:10:04,541 --> 00:10:06,341
It is an honor to present
this prestigious award tonight.

209
00:10:06,374 --> 00:10:08,207
[DRUMROLL PLAYING]

210
00:10:08,241 --> 00:10:09,841
And now, the moment
we've all been waiting for.

211
00:10:09,874 --> 00:10:13,174
The winner of the
Robot of the Year award is...

212
00:10:13,207 --> 00:10:15,574
Hi, Harley! Don't forget
to thank me in your speech.

213
00:10:20,807 --> 00:10:23,607
KATO:
Every year, these award shows
run longer and longer.

214
00:10:23,641 --> 00:10:26,807
And now...

215
00:10:26,841 --> 00:10:30,307
Best Achievement
in Special Effects...

216
00:10:30,341 --> 00:10:31,241
me!

217
00:10:37,674 --> 00:10:39,607
[PEOPLE SCREAMING]

218
00:10:39,641 --> 00:10:40,707
MAN:
What's happening?

219
00:10:40,741 --> 00:10:41,774
[GRUNTS]

220
00:10:41,807 --> 00:10:43,207
What on earth happened?

221
00:10:46,141 --> 00:10:49,041
Oh! Volcano!

222
00:10:50,541 --> 00:10:52,207
[RUMBLING]

223
00:10:52,241 --> 00:10:54,407
Why, that's Caldera Island!

224
00:10:54,441 --> 00:10:56,541
CAPTAIN:
But that's 100 miles
off our course!

225
00:10:56,574 --> 00:11:00,374
It's also unlikely the volcano
could have erupted on its own.

226
00:11:00,407 --> 00:11:04,307
Captain...this ship's navigation
is off-line!

227
00:11:04,341 --> 00:11:06,141
We're headed
straight for the volcano!

228
00:11:06,174 --> 00:11:07,574
Then reverse course
manually!

229
00:11:07,607 --> 00:11:09,674
All crew members return
to their stations immediately!

230
00:11:09,707 --> 00:11:11,341
SHIPMAN:
Someone hacked
the computer!

231
00:11:11,374 --> 00:11:14,074
We're locked out of the system,
including manual controls.

232
00:11:17,874 --> 00:11:19,507
Ahh!

233
00:11:19,541 --> 00:11:22,541
Crashing the ship looks like
the least of our problems.

234
00:11:22,574 --> 00:11:24,307
Harley, protect the others.

235
00:11:24,341 --> 00:11:26,341
Epsilon, let's rocket!

236
00:11:26,374 --> 00:11:28,507
We have to turn
this ship around now!

237
00:11:28,541 --> 00:11:31,041
[GRUNTS]

238
00:11:33,741 --> 00:11:36,141
[GRUNTS]

239
00:11:36,174 --> 00:11:37,341
DRAKE:
Sometimes I need to

240
00:11:37,374 --> 00:11:39,841
get out of the office
to clear my head.

241
00:11:39,874 --> 00:11:41,741
And trashing robots
in a rain of fire,

242
00:11:41,774 --> 00:11:44,274
that beats golf
any day of the week.

243
00:11:44,307 --> 00:11:46,107
[LAUGHS]

244
00:11:48,574 --> 00:11:50,574
[DR. O'SHAY PANTING]

245
00:11:50,607 --> 00:11:52,507
We're running out of time.
Have you hacked back in?

246
00:11:52,541 --> 00:11:54,041
No, sir.

247
00:11:55,674 --> 00:11:58,741
The passcodes have been
changed, and we are
denied access.

248
00:11:58,774 --> 00:12:00,441
ROBOT:
Perhaps
I can help.

249
00:12:02,407 --> 00:12:04,174
Clark, I can't think
of anyone

250
00:12:04,207 --> 00:12:05,607
more qualified
for the job than you.

251
00:12:09,741 --> 00:12:11,374
[COMPUTER BEEPS]

252
00:12:11,407 --> 00:12:14,574
Hmm, this is
a very strong encryption.

253
00:12:14,607 --> 00:12:15,807
Fascinating!

254
00:12:15,841 --> 00:12:17,407
I've never seen it before.

255
00:12:17,441 --> 00:12:19,174
[GRUNTING]

256
00:12:33,140 --> 00:12:38,006
Maybe working together, we can
turn the ship around somehow.

257
00:12:38,040 --> 00:12:39,973
[GRUNTS]

258
00:12:40,006 --> 00:12:43,006
Yes, but that would leave
the ship unprotected.

259
00:12:43,040 --> 00:12:45,540
DRAKE:
Looks like I've left Astro

260
00:12:45,573 --> 00:12:48,140
between a rock
and a hot place.

261
00:12:48,173 --> 00:12:50,406
[LAUGHS]

262
00:12:52,073 --> 00:12:53,106
[WHIMPERING]

263
00:12:55,940 --> 00:12:57,406
What?
What's happening?

264
00:12:59,540 --> 00:13:01,373
The volcano! It's gonna blow!

265
00:13:05,440 --> 00:13:07,340
[PANTS]

266
00:13:07,373 --> 00:13:09,340
Buddy!

267
00:13:09,373 --> 00:13:11,840
Uh! Oh!

268
00:13:11,873 --> 00:13:15,840
Buddy! He's in the jungle
and he may need help!

269
00:13:15,873 --> 00:13:17,340
Huh?

270
00:13:17,373 --> 00:13:20,040
Talk about timing.

271
00:13:20,073 --> 00:13:23,206
Hey! Hey, I'm here!
I'm here!

272
00:13:25,273 --> 00:13:26,773
Mr. Drake!

273
00:13:26,806 --> 00:13:28,473
Climb onboard!

274
00:13:28,506 --> 00:13:30,840
How did you ever find me here?

275
00:13:30,873 --> 00:13:33,040
From your transmission!

276
00:13:33,073 --> 00:13:35,173
You've been broadcasting
an SOS, didn't you know?

277
00:13:35,206 --> 00:13:36,373
No, I--

278
00:13:36,406 --> 00:13:39,340
Is there
something wrong,
Mr. Drake?

279
00:13:39,373 --> 00:13:41,540
[MACHINE BEEPS RAPIDLY]

280
00:13:41,573 --> 00:13:43,540
Buddy sent the signal.
And now you can
help me find him.

281
00:13:43,573 --> 00:13:45,140
Who's Buddy?

282
00:13:45,173 --> 00:13:47,406
Are there any other people
here besides you, sir?

283
00:13:47,440 --> 00:13:48,940
Buddy's a...robot.

284
00:13:48,973 --> 00:13:51,073
We don't have time
to go look for a robot!

285
00:13:51,106 --> 00:13:52,540
Sir, you need to
come with us!

286
00:13:52,573 --> 00:13:55,040
I'm not leaving this island
without him.

287
00:13:55,073 --> 00:13:56,073
Buddy!

288
00:13:56,106 --> 00:13:58,006
Come back!

289
00:13:58,040 --> 00:13:59,540
That's right,
Buddy isn't just a robot.

290
00:13:59,573 --> 00:14:01,006
He...he took care of me.

291
00:14:01,040 --> 00:14:02,973
I can't abandon him!

292
00:14:03,006 --> 00:14:04,006
I won't!

293
00:14:04,040 --> 00:14:06,273
[GRUNTS]

294
00:14:10,306 --> 00:14:12,773
[GRUNTING]

295
00:14:22,306 --> 00:14:23,540
Buddy.

296
00:14:23,573 --> 00:14:25,973
Leave the robot.
It's just a tool.

297
00:14:26,006 --> 00:14:27,273
Just a tool?

298
00:14:27,306 --> 00:14:28,840
That's right,
sir.

299
00:14:28,873 --> 00:14:31,406
In the end,
it's people that
matter, not robots.

300
00:14:31,440 --> 00:14:34,340
Yes. Yes, of course.

301
00:14:38,973 --> 00:14:42,273
A robot...not a real person.

302
00:14:42,306 --> 00:14:45,973
It was probably...
already too late.

303
00:14:46,006 --> 00:14:47,040
Hey!

304
00:14:47,073 --> 00:14:48,773
It's not possible!

305
00:14:52,340 --> 00:14:53,973
Buddy, forgive me.

306
00:15:04,573 --> 00:15:05,940
[WHIMPERS]

307
00:15:11,573 --> 00:15:13,440
[PEOPLE SCREAMING]

308
00:15:13,473 --> 00:15:14,973
MAN:
There's nothing we can do!

309
00:15:15,006 --> 00:15:16,473
Help us.

310
00:15:17,540 --> 00:15:19,073
Listen up!

311
00:15:19,106 --> 00:15:20,906
The robots are doing
everything they can,

312
00:15:20,940 --> 00:15:21,973
but there's plenty
we can do too.

313
00:15:22,006 --> 00:15:25,140
ZORAN:
I found
a first aid kit.

314
00:15:25,173 --> 00:15:26,240
Thanks.

315
00:15:26,273 --> 00:15:27,540
[GRUNTS]

316
00:15:27,573 --> 00:15:29,773
I got things handled over here.

317
00:15:29,806 --> 00:15:32,240
Dr. O'Shay is right.
There's work to be done.

318
00:15:32,273 --> 00:15:34,040
Yeah, we can
help each other.

319
00:15:34,073 --> 00:15:36,173
MAN:
Come on, let's start by
moving the wounded to safety.

320
00:15:36,206 --> 00:15:37,173
MAN 2:
Okay.

321
00:15:37,206 --> 00:15:39,306
MAN 3:
Here, help me get this man
by the table.

322
00:15:39,340 --> 00:15:42,473
DRAKE:
This is O'Shay's fault,
the old fool!

323
00:15:42,506 --> 00:15:45,073
Making robots with <i>kokoro.</i>

324
00:15:46,173 --> 00:15:47,373
And me...

325
00:15:47,406 --> 00:15:50,006
I must have been deluded...

326
00:15:50,040 --> 00:15:51,873
thinking that a robot
could have been my friend.

327
00:15:53,273 --> 00:15:54,973
FACTORY CHIEF:
<i>I'm proud to say</i>

328
00:15:55,006 --> 00:15:56,840
we've completed mass production
<i>on our newest line.</i>

329
00:15:56,873 --> 00:16:00,806
I think you'll be pleased
with the result, Mr. Drake.

330
00:16:00,840 --> 00:16:03,240
I give you
the most advanced

331
00:16:03,273 --> 00:16:05,906
artificial intelligence
robot on the market.

332
00:16:05,940 --> 00:16:07,140
What?!

333
00:16:11,106 --> 00:16:14,240
What is this?
What...what have you done?

334
00:16:14,273 --> 00:16:16,406
BUDDY'S VOICE:
Why?

335
00:16:16,440 --> 00:16:17,506
[WHIMPERS]

336
00:16:17,540 --> 00:16:20,173
Why did you leave me there?

337
00:16:20,206 --> 00:16:22,040
You said I was your buddy.

338
00:16:22,073 --> 00:16:23,973
No.

339
00:16:24,006 --> 00:16:25,340
Stop it!

340
00:16:25,373 --> 00:16:27,006
No!

341
00:16:27,040 --> 00:16:29,040
Equipped with the latest
artificial hearts and minds,

342
00:16:29,073 --> 00:16:31,206
you could say
they're almost human.

343
00:16:31,240 --> 00:16:32,506
Enough!

344
00:16:32,540 --> 00:16:34,806
<i>The last thing</i>
<i>this world needs</i>

345
00:16:34,840 --> 00:16:37,073
<i>is a lot of</i>
<i>soulless machines</i>

346
00:16:37,106 --> 00:16:39,840
<i>tricking us into thinking</i>
<i>that they're human.</i>

347
00:16:39,873 --> 00:16:42,140
<i>It's not gonna happen</i>
<i>on my watch!</i>

348
00:16:43,373 --> 00:16:44,340
CLARK:
I am in!

349
00:16:44,373 --> 00:16:46,540
I broke the encryption!

350
00:16:46,573 --> 00:16:48,440
Now to get this ship
turned around

351
00:16:48,473 --> 00:16:51,440
and away
from that volcano.

352
00:16:55,206 --> 00:16:56,806
Astro, look!

353
00:16:56,840 --> 00:16:58,373
The ship is
turning around!

354
00:16:58,406 --> 00:17:00,106
Great!

355
00:17:00,140 --> 00:17:02,040
But...she's not
out of danger yet.

356
00:17:02,073 --> 00:17:03,373
Huh?

357
00:17:10,340 --> 00:17:12,773
EPSILON:
Astro!

358
00:17:12,806 --> 00:17:14,806
What can we do?

359
00:17:18,273 --> 00:17:19,973
I love a big finish!

360
00:17:21,806 --> 00:17:23,340
[GROANS]

361
00:17:34,040 --> 00:17:34,973
ZORAN:
It's Astro!

362
00:17:35,006 --> 00:17:37,040
[ALL LAUGH]

363
00:17:37,073 --> 00:17:38,840
No one told me he could do that!

364
00:17:38,873 --> 00:17:39,906
Oh!

365
00:17:43,340 --> 00:17:45,873
Oh! I'm losing altitude!

366
00:17:50,173 --> 00:17:51,540
There.

367
00:17:51,573 --> 00:17:52,740
Huh?

368
00:17:54,873 --> 00:17:56,540
[GRUNTS]

369
00:17:56,573 --> 00:17:57,840
[SCREAMS]

370
00:18:00,273 --> 00:18:01,073
[ASTRO GRUNTS]

371
00:18:04,906 --> 00:18:08,140
Everybody's safe now
thanks to Astro and Epsilon.

372
00:18:08,173 --> 00:18:09,373
[PEOPLE CHEERING]

373
00:18:09,406 --> 00:18:11,106
MAN:
Epsilon...
you saved us!

374
00:18:11,140 --> 00:18:12,540
Thank you very much!

375
00:18:12,573 --> 00:18:13,806
Mmm!

376
00:18:15,440 --> 00:18:16,873
MAN:
Yeah! Good job,
Epsilon!

377
00:18:16,906 --> 00:18:18,306
[CHUCKLES]

378
00:18:18,340 --> 00:18:19,873
MAN:
And Astro too!

379
00:18:24,940 --> 00:18:28,073
Come on. Come on, start!

380
00:18:28,106 --> 00:18:30,840
Do you need any help?
Are you okay in there?

381
00:18:30,873 --> 00:18:32,440
[DISGUISING VOICE]
I'm fine!

382
00:18:32,473 --> 00:18:35,240
Now get away from my ship before
you cause any more damage!

383
00:18:36,873 --> 00:18:38,173
ASTRO:
Hey!

384
00:18:44,140 --> 00:18:46,440
Now, that's a guy
that needs <i>kokoro.</i>

385
00:18:46,473 --> 00:18:49,806
I wonder who he was.

386
00:18:52,206 --> 00:18:53,306
REPORTER:
<i>This morning,</i>

387
00:18:53,340 --> 00:18:55,406
<i>the</i> Carmela Queen
arrived safely in port.

388
00:18:55,440 --> 00:18:57,240
<i>Thanks to this year's</i>
<i>robot nominees,</i>

389
00:18:57,273 --> 00:18:59,473
<i>no one onboard</i>
<i>was seriously hurt.</i>

390
00:18:59,506 --> 00:19:01,840
<i>In recognition</i>
<i>of their heroism,</i>

391
00:19:01,873 --> 00:19:04,206
<i>the judges decided that</i>
<i>the Robot of the Year award</i>

392
00:19:04,240 --> 00:19:07,106
<i>would be split among</i>
<i>all five nominees.</i>

393
00:19:07,140 --> 00:19:09,006
<i>The cause</i>
<i>of the mysterious incident</i>

394
00:19:09,040 --> 00:19:11,173
<i>is still</i>
<i>under investigation.</i>

395
00:19:13,240 --> 00:19:15,540
DRAKE:
Medals and ribbons
prove nothing.

396
00:19:15,573 --> 00:19:17,873
Robots are soulless tools.

397
00:19:17,906 --> 00:19:20,140
They have no need of <i>kokoro.</i>

398
00:19:20,173 --> 00:19:22,840
DAN:
Hey, that's Caldera Island,
where we dug you up.

399
00:19:24,506 --> 00:19:25,840
I wonder
what happened

400
00:19:25,873 --> 00:19:27,473
to the person
who called me Buddy.

401
00:19:27,506 --> 00:19:30,040
I hope
he's doing well.

402
00:19:30,073 --> 00:19:32,473
DAN:
It's too bad you don't
remember his name,

403
00:19:32,506 --> 00:19:35,440
but unfortunately,
<i>your memory chip</i>
<i>was too badly damaged.</i>

404
00:19:35,473 --> 00:19:37,106
Something
wrong?

405
00:19:37,140 --> 00:19:38,340
No, I guess not.

406
00:19:38,373 --> 00:19:39,773
Then come on.

407
00:19:39,806 --> 00:19:42,173
I'll buy you a cup
of antifreeze.

408
00:19:52,940 --> 00:19:54,906
[♪]

